package ThreadingDefaultClass;

public class SynchronizationDemo implements Runnable {


	public synchronized void  printNums(){
		
		for(int i=1; i <= 10;i ++) {
			
			System.out.println(Thread.currentThread().getName()+"-->"+i);
			
			try{Thread.sleep(1000);
		}catch(Exception e){
			
			e.printStackTrace();
			}
		}
		
	}
		
	
	public void run() {
      
		
		printNums();
	}


public static void main(String[] args) {
	
	SynchronizationDemo d = new SynchronizationDemo();
	
	Thread t1 = new Thread(d);
	t1.setName("Thread..1");
	t1.start();
	
	Thread t2 = new Thread(d);
	t1.setName("Thread..2");
	t2.start();
}

}














Note: in the above program we are starting 2 threads, two threads will access printNum() method to print the numbers from 1 to 10.

-> If printNums() method having synchronized keyword then two threads will execute the method sequencially one after other.
-> If we remove synchronied keyword from the printNum() method then two threads will access that method at a time.
